<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06299277 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06299277 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: 'A new and more intimate relationship is being demanded amongautomobiles, humans and the Earth.  '-- Shoichiro Toyoda,; Toyota Motor Corp.President  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  JAPAN; AUTO; FUTURE; SUPPORT; ENVIRONMENT; CONSERVATION  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  For Japanese automakers, the future may be uncertain, but its color isecological green.;   They are betting that an emphasis on environmental anduser-friendly models will help them overcome a stalled world auto market andcope with pollution and global-warming worries.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  LATEST CARS SHOW JAPANESE HAVE HEEDEDENVIRONMENTALISTS  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     In a shift from the larger luxury models released in the last two years bymany Japanese makers, this year's Tokyo Motor Show that opens this weekend isfilled with smaller, environmentally correct vehicles that stresshuman-oriented design.;   &quot;We must understand that a new and more intimaterelationship is being demanded among automobiles, humans and the Earth,&quot; saidToyota Motor Corp. President Shoichiro Toyoda.;   A record 352 companies from13 countries are represented at the weeklong show, including 30 from theUnited States.;   U.S. Undersecretary of Commerce for International TradeMichael Farren, in Japan to open the U.S. booth, said the participation ofAmerican manufacturers &quot;illustrates the importance U.S. companies are placingon the Japanese auto market,&quot; which ranks second in size after the UnitedStates.;   Farren warned that calls will grow for more restrictions onJapanese cars in the United States if American automakers are unable to sellmore in Japan.;   But U.S. booths at the show had few new &quot;concept cars,&quot; andthe cars they exhibited looked stodgy and cumbersome next to those displayedby Japanese makers, and attracted fewer reporters.;   Many Japanese models atthe show boast lean-burning engines, bodies made of lightweight, recyclablematerials, and a dazzling array of high-tech yet practical gadgets.;   &quot;Thetheme of the show is how to deal with the stagnation of the economy worldwideand with environmental problems,&quot; Honda Motor Corp. President NobuhikoKawamoto told reporters at a press preview.;   He said Honda decided to begindisplaying &quot;concept cars&quot; at this year's show because of major changes likelyin the industry in coming years.;   &quot;The market is in confusion,&quot; he said.&quot;It's necessary to plan for change.&quot;;   Among the exhibits at the biennialshow, Japan's leading display of auto technology, is Honda's EP-X, for&quot;efficient personal experimental,&quot; which combines an efficient engine with anall-aluminum body for a total weight of less than 1,364 lbs.;   The driversits in the middle in a one-person front seat, while a single passenger sitsdirectly behind, cradled by the car's body like an egg for greater safety,Honda says.;   A color LCD screen next to the driver displays engine and speeddata, or, with the push of a button, shows a rear view from a video cameramounted at the back of the car.;   Toyota describes its experimental AXV-IIIas &quot;the gentler sedan of the future.&quot;;   Nissan Motor Co. says it designed itsCocoon for &quot;the new more closely knit families of the future.&quot;;   Instead of adoor key, the car has a fingerprint detector that admits people it recognizes,and then automatically adjusts the driving position to that person's pre-setpreference.;   An automatic drowsiness detector monitors the driver's actionsand releases a refreshing scent and sounds a buzzer when it detects sleepydriving patterns.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Chiba, Japan  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911025  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  October  </MONTH><PG.COL>  10D  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  536  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Friday, October 25, 199100299277,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>